Since the period is monthly, we will divide the annual percentage rate by the number of months in a year. Hence, we will express the rate in the following equation in our calculation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.0535}{12}

\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of the annuity.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$925\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+\dfrac{0.0535}{12}\right)^{360}}}{\dfrac{0.0535}{12}}
\\[20pt]
&=\$925\times\dfrac{0.7983925}{0.004458333}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$165,647.80}
\end{aligned}$$


Hence, as can be seen in our calculation, the present value of the annuity is $165,647.80.

Next, considering the present value of the annuity, let's now calculate the balloon payment.

The balloon payment refers to the large sum of one-time payments typically at the end of the loan period. We can calculate the balloon payment by subtracting the present value of the annuity from the cost of the house to be purchased. Hence we can calculate the balloon payment with the following formula:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Balloon Payment} &= \text{Cost of the house}-\text{Present value of the annuity}
\end{aligned}$$
